How do you handle conditional rendering in LWC? Explain if:true, if:false, lwc:if, and lwc:else
Companies that asked this: TCS, Infosys, Capgemini, Salesforce, Accenture, Wipro

Answer:
LWC provides several ways to handle conditional rendering. Let me explain each approach and when to use them:

Legacy Approach (Still supported):

if:true and if:false - Simple boolean conditionals

Works with any boolean expression

Modern Approach (Recommended):

lwc:if - More powerful conditional rendering

lwc:elseif - Multiple conditions

lwc:else - Default fallback

Better performance and more readable

Example:

export default class ConditionalExample extends LightningElement {
    isLoading = false;
    hasError = false;
    accounts = [];
    userRole = 'admin';
    
    get hasData() {
        return this.accounts.length > 0;
    }
    
    get isAdmin() {
        return this.userRole === 'admin';
    }
}
HTML:

<template>
    <!-- LEGACY: if:true and if:false -->
    <div if:true={isLoading}>Loading...</div>
    <div if:false={isLoading}>Content loaded</div>
    
    <button if:true={isAdmin}>Admin Action</button>
    
    <!-- MODERN: lwc:if, lwc:elseif, lwc:else -->
    <div lwc:if={isLoading}>
        <lightning-spinner></lightning-spinner>
    </div>
    
    <div lwc:elseif={hasError}>
        <p>Error occurred!</p>
    </div>
    
    <div lwc:elseif={hasData}>
        <p>Showing {accounts.length} accounts</p>
    </div>
    
    <div lwc:else>
        <p>No data available</p>
    </div>
</template>
